<p class="posted">posted by <a rel="nofollow" href="http://ashley.hatken.com/weblog/">Ashley Aitken</a>
 on August 23, 2006 <a href="visitingmit#c7" rel="bookmark">#</a></p>
</div>
<div id="c8">
<p>My preferred definition of nostalgia for a long time has been Fernando Savater&#8217;s: &#8220;Nostalgia is to search oneself where one is no more: and to be painfully surprised of such absence.&#8221; Yours is a slightly different kind, the particular instance of which (academ-algia) I deeply share, it&#8217;s searching oneself somewhere that never existed: and being painfully surprised of such absence.</p>

<p>Personally, my favorite scholarly mirage is Tarnover, the government school for gifted youngsters described in John Brunner&#8217;s Shockwave Rider.</p>

<p class="posted">posted by <a rel="nofollow" href="http://elzr.com">elzr</a>
